erbert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German, English, and French: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. In Britain, this Old French name, introduced by the Normans, reinforced the less common Old English cognate <i>Herebeorht</i>. The surname was taken to Ireland after the Anglo-Norman invasion and in the 16th century.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the German personal name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Harbison","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert   (the change from <i>-er-</i> to <i>-ar-</i> was a common one in Old French and Middle English). An intrusive <i>n</i> later gave   Harbinson  ."]},{"name":"Hebard","meanings":["English (Surrey):","variant of   Herbert  , with assimilation of the first <i>r</i>. Compare   Hebb  .","variant of   Hibbert  ."]},{"name":"Harbert","meanings":["German and English: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbers","meanings":["German and Dutch: patronymic from   Herbert  . It is found mainly in Lower Saxony and across the Dutch border."]},{"name":"Dickherber","meanings":["Probably a nickname for a fat person by the name of   Herbert  , of which <i>Herber</i> is a short form, or, more likely, in the north from <b>Die(c)kherber</b>, a topographic and distinguishing name for a <i>Herber</i> living by the dike, see   Dicke   2. Compare   Dickmeyer  ."]},{"name":"Hebert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Emile, Normand, Jacques, Marcel, Pierre, Lucien, Michel, Gaston, Alcide, Camille.","French (<b>Hébert</b>): assimilated form of   Herbert  . Compare   Abair  ,   Abar  ,   Abare  ,   Abear  ,   Aber  ,   Eber  , and   Ebert  .","German: variant of   Heber   1."]},{"name":"Herber","meanings":["German and Dutch: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbertson","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Hebb","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire and northeast Midlands): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hebb</i>, <i>Ebb</i>, pet forms of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herb","meanings":["South German: nickname for a harsh or rough person, from Middle High German <i>herb</i> ‘tart, harsh’.","German: from the personal name <i>Herpo</i>, a pet form of   Herbert  ."]}]},{"name":"Finch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>finch</i>, <i>fink</i> ‘finch’ (Old English <i>finc</i>), for a small, lively, cheerful person.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German, Jewish (Ashkenazic), Czech, Slovenian, and Croatian   Fink   ‘finch’, or of some of the corresponding Slavic surnames, e.g. Czech (Moravian) <b>Pěnka</b> (see   Penka  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Fink","meanings":["German, Jewish (Ashkenazic), Danish, and English: nickname for a lively and cheerful person, or, in the case of the Jewish name, an artificial name, from Middle High German <i>vinke</i>, Middle English and Yiddish <i>fink</i> ‘finch’ (see   Finch   and   Vink  ). The surname of German origin is also found in some central European countries, for example in Czechia, Slovenia, and Croatia, often as a translation into German of corresponding Slavic nicknames or surnames. In part, this is a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname, originating from the Kočevsko region in Lower Carniola, Slovenia (see   Kocevar  )."]}]},{"name":"Vincent","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vincens</i> ‘conquering’ (genitive <i>Vincentis</i>). This name was borne by various early saints particularly associated with France, most notably the 5th-century  St Vincent of Lérins ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":18,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":43,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":56,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":65,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":110,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Vincent Herbert Finch was born about 1272, in Winchelsea, Sussex, England. She married Vincent Herbert Finch I about 1293. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1272–":"umbes 1272–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1295–